segments.text: These guys weren't that much bigger than I was.
And I was small.
And you look at some of the kids today that play football particularly, but even basketball, and they're lots bigger than the kids back then.
We had, you know, Stallings wasn't much bigger than I was.
And a college kid that weighed 200 pounds
Well, Charlie Kruger was one of the largest.
Yeah.
And Pardee, Crowe, they probably as seniors barely made 200.
But Gene Stoll was probably 170.
Bobby Marks was 155, 160.
Randy Sims was not that big.
Bobby Drake Keith.
And several of them made the pros.
You know, St. Louis, I think two or three Aggies when they graduated here went to St. Louis.
Cardinals had played for years.
As far as you students knew, did those Bear Bryant athletes go to class?
I saw several of them in my classes.
Did y'all ever hear- Roper was a senior, a center, and he was an ag major.
Did y'all ever hear of any- Well, Murray Trimble, I don't know if Murray ever went.
The reputation on campus was that he was a hell raiser.
But as far as I know,
They were in class, but I couldn't vouch for it.
But y'all didn't hear any stories about any classes specifically for athletes only?
I didn't.
I don't think there were any.
I'm not aware of it.
Let's see.
What was Yale practice like in that time?
Well, his pinky down was cutting off his tie and throwing it out.
And of course, there were always some Aggie fables told by the yell leaders.
And it was held where?
It was over in the Grove.
In the Grove.
Yeah.
And it was just another one of those sweat times when sophomores just loved to chew on freshmen.
What hour of the Friday night?
Usually it was about midnight.
So it really was at midnight.
Yes.
And we would have sometimes more than one yell practice in a week because we marched right after supper over and spent about an hour getting ready for an opponent that weekend.
But yell practice on Friday night was at midnight.
All right, Secretary, don't type this in here.
It's not part of it.
One of RC's suggestions for the leadership to consider is to move Yale practice earlier on Friday night so the team can go and participate in the enthusiasm
and know of the support they have, and to have Yale practice at, say, 8 o'clock.
And still get a good night's sleep.
And still get a good night's sleep, which I think is a good idea.
But apparently that's getting a lot of second thought by students saying, no, no, we've never done it that way before.
Well, we have.
It used to be earlier during the week if we had the Yelp practice on a Thursday or on a Wednesday.
And it was always in the grove, all four years?
I don't remember having Yelp practice any place but the grove.
Describe, then,
home game Saturday.
What time did things start?
What did take through the whole day?
Well, you'd fall out about the same time that we did during the regular weekday, about 6.
We'd march over to Sabisa or Duncan, eat,
and then come back and usually had a room inspection.
Well, you went to class.
Well, we had Saturday morning classes.

But we'd usually have, on Saturday, we'd usually have a room inspection to see that everything was ship shape and we knew how to make a bed and we knew how to, and this was usually with a military science officer being accompanied by the first sergeant and CO.

Then we would fall out usually about, if it was a 2 o'clock game, we'd fall out about 12.30 or 1 and march over as a unit and move up into the freshman section and sophomore section and juniors and seniors.
I think that's even precedent today, at least in the court.
And then participate in the yelling at the game.
Those things haven't changed a whole lot.
We stood up.
The uniform, of course, was worn all week.
Anytime you were on campus, you were in uniform.
As you recall, what were some of your happiest football games and your most unhappy, disappointed games?

Well of course the winning against the University of Texas was a thrill because it had been a bunch of years since we had won a Texas game but being here with Bear Bryant's era you got the impression that A&M had always been good
had always won, and when Hank Fulberg and Jim Fry came as coaches in the 60s and 70s, you just couldn't believe what had happened.
It was difficult surviving those years after being spoiled with your introduction as an Aggie to the Bear Bind era.
Now, we had the tough 58 with the Rice and the Texas loss, two points and one point.
But other than that, every time we played, we expected to win.
I mean, seriously expected to win.
It wasn't a fantasy.
Were you at that Rice game?
Yes.
What did you guys do after it was over?
Just stood there and tried to get out of shock.
Same way with Texas.
Even though it had been tempered that, well, A&M might be beaten because you just didn't entertain that.
I mean, it was something that was so ridiculous that you just didn't entertain the thought that we had two more games won.
And describe a typical G. Raleigh White home basketball game for you students.
very much like a football game.
We filled the place and we yelled and at that time of course you didn't think about it but the players were all white.
And I was trying to think of the first
colored basketball player that A&M had.
It was shortly after.
Must have been Shelby's third or fourth year as head coach.
Because I can't remember his name, but I remember when that happened.
Let's see.
I think SMU had had a black player the year before, and then A&M had recruited a black player.
And the whole band was at the basketball games.
Yeah.
The band came, and then half of the Corps, essentially, the Army units had one home game, and then the Air Force would have the next one.
And so you got to go, and I don't ever remember seeing tickets.
Of course, when we went to football games, I don't ever remember seeing a ticket that I had.
We marched into the game, and then essentially filed up into the stands like the band does now.
We didn't march back out.
So I'm sure that somewhere in there, there were tickets purchased.
But the CO or first sergeant handled all those.
What did you and your buddies think about the Aggie Band?
I think we were really envious because they got to do a lot of traveling.
But we were impressed by the band's performance.
We were always proud of the Aggie band.
How much prestige did the band commander have among student leaders?
That was David Eller as a senior.
None particular.
Not at all comparable to corps commander?
No.
And on the campus when you were president of student government,
Did you feel that you were equal to the Corps commander in prestige?
No.
Don Cloud's position was very, very unique and highly respected.
But after that, what was next in prestige?
Well, the whole Corps staff, I think, from the standpoint of this total student body, once you became familiar with what went on down here,
I think the core staff members were viewed as being the leadership on campus.
Then you had the student senate and the officers of each class.
What about your leaders?
They were in a class by themselves.
That was a different kind of leadership.

they were responsible for the morale of Aggies so they fit a little different mold they weren't expected to behave the same as a class president or a corps staff member Smokey Hyde for instance wasn't
expected to do the same things that Don Cloud did.
What about RVs?
Very worthy, sought after opportunity.
Very unique group.
Only the very best would be able to become a Ross volunteer.
had the unique opportunity to be the governor's honor guard and to go to New Orleans.
Were you an RV?
Yes.
Until I got kicked out.
For what?
For missing too many practices as chairman of...
This was your senior year?
No, junior year.
Junior year.
Yeah, I had gotten in RVs, gotten a uniform, had drilled with them for about two months,
And then I had a student government conference and a Texas state science convention.
And I didn't know that that could happen.
Got back and had been gone two weeks, and they said, if you can't drill, you can't be with us.
Now, how did you learn that you were going to be a member?
Because you didn't run for it.
You weren't elected.
I think the military science department selected.
I'm not even sure.
I got a letter indicating that I had been selected as a Ross volunteer.
So you didn't apply.
You weren't interviewed.
I wasn't.
I didn't.
I just got a letter indicating that I had been selected as a Ross Volunteer.
And I believe that that letter was signed by Colonel Joe Davis, the Commandant of Military Science.
What did you do with the uniform after you were dropped?
Did you keep it, turn it back?
I believe that it was checked out.
I don't even remember
What happened to the uniform after I was booted out of the Ross Volunteers?
All right.
Did you know that when you were a student, did you know there were some secret fraternities?
Oh, yeah.
Well, there was the mole men that by reputation controlled the campus and lived down in the steam tunnels.
Never knowingly met a mole man.
But about 90% of the people that I knew were reportedly in that organization.
And they were always being quoted in the bat, not by name, but as a bone man.
What about, did you hear of the TTs and the stickers?
Not I.
Really?
What was the purpose of the Mole Men as far as you knew?
To represent the student body in issues on campus relating to those student gripes and things that we didn't appreciate and to try to control the
staff over at the Military Science Department that were always there watching every unit.
It was an opportunity to let off steam.
Now let's see, there were, the impact of veterans on the student body during your day was comparatively small.
Yes, there were very few here.
We didn't have a war that ended where they came back here in any significant numbers.
So almost all of the students were right out of high school.
Essentially.
So let's return back to the diversity.
Were there some Jewish kids that you knew?
Not that I was aware of.
I'm sure that there were in our outfit, but they didn't stand out.
They weren't different.
Were there any international students?
Not really.
We had a few graduate students, and I can remember in entomology there were one or two from India.
Were there many students from other states?
Not really.
I don't remember any in our outfit.
They were all from Texas.
Alright, what was it that drew these students together, whatever they were from?
Why were y'all?
I think the core.
It shaped and formed everything other than your academic life.
And so, in many respects, about the only difference is whether you came from the city or whether you came from the country.
And there were some differences.

in that respect in your history and your experiences and how you thought but those fairly quickly vanished as far as you became the same when you put on the same clothes you have to go through the same drill and harassment you're taking the same courses there's a lot of uniformity that took place
We didn't have people, as I always say, we didn't have none of my friends that shaved their legs out here.
And what were the events that contributed most?
You mentioned the Corps.
What else, what are the events, the activities that contributed most to that unity, that spirit?

the harassment and the recognition that if you were going to survive you'd better stick together because if you got separated you got the good fortune of having five or six sophomores on you all at one time so it was the recognition that you were in this thing together
and that the only way you were gonna survive was to have five or six fish buddies with you all the time.
All right, so teamwork.
Absolutely.
And what about Yale practice and football games and bonfire?
Those were the opportunity to get away from the dorm life.
And there weren't a whole lot of those as you look back and you look at what this campus and being an Aggie today is about.
But I think our expectations were a lot different.
We hadn't come from a background that had to be entertained, that had to have air conditioning.
I'd never seen TV when I came to A&M.
There was a TV in a hardware store on the square in Wellington.
It wasn't Sullivan's.
It sat in the window, but all you could see was snow.
And Saturday night when we'd go to town to get groceries, there'd be a big crowd watching that silly TV set and all you could see was snow.
You couldn't see figures on it.
But I saw my first TV set in the MSC.
It wasn't really good, and it was small, but I saw my first TV set there.
These other activities, do you remember your first silver taps?
Not vividly, but I remember silver taps and the solemnness and how quiet things were and how dark it was.
Did you and your buddies take it seriously?
Yes.
It was a very reverent time.
Generally we knew the individual personally that had been killed because by and large you knew every student on this campus.
Some you couldn't remember their names, but they usually helped you every time you forgot.
They helped you remember the next time.
But it was a very moving experience.
to everyone because you knew that person.
And it was a little bit like having a cousin.
Did you go to Muster?
Yes.
Where was it held?
It was held in G. Raleigh.
And what did that seem to be to you?
A daytime silver tap.
It was very solemn.
Muster hadn't changed all that much.
RVs came in and fired.
Many of the same activities that happened today happened in the 50s and probably the 30s and the 20s at Muster.
You would have an Aggie speaker that talked about their experiences.
Then the names of those that had passed away would be called off.
Someone would answer here.
And it was one of those experiences that you remember because of its impact on you.
Your senior boots, how much did they cost?
Where'd you get them?
From a senior that graduated the year before.
And they almost fit.
And how long did you keep them?
That year.
When I graduated, I sold them to a junior.
Did you make any profit?
No.
They sold for about $75 a year for break-even.
Did you enjoy wearing them?
What did senior boots mean to you internally?
Well, they represented achieving something you'd spent three years trying to achieve.

and it was you just knew that that that was impressive and you didn't know for sure a lot of times I can remember Fish Van Zant and I fortunately we both didn't decide to quit at the same time we'd take time we'd swap off

I'd come in disgusted about something or down about something and be ready to quit and go home and Fish Van Zant would say, no, we can't do that and give me all the reasons and then next week would be his time to be ready to quit.
But it was, you had paid your dues and it was something that you felt like was earned and was worth

what you'd invested in it and I I've always used the bonfire collapse thing you could read articles and you could tell whether someone who had been around this place wrote the article in the first two paragraphs or if it was someone from the international media that really didn't know what A&M was about and

I've always thought it was funny that people didn't understand and you couldn't explain exactly to them what it's like and unless you've lived through it you really can't my kids both said daddy you didn't really do that did you and about half the things that I say is they didn't believe
How did you feel wearing those boots for the first time at the final review as you were a junior?
They were very uncomfortable, but I wasn't going to ever admit it.
Clumsy.
I'd worn boots, cowboy boots, all my life, so part of it wasn't all that new.
But you felt very proud, but they weren't really that comfortable.
You were awkward.
For you, were there any special people in the audience that day at Final Review your junior year?
My mom and dad came down.
And when did you?
All of your buddies were there.
That had become family.
It really had.
By the end of your freshman year, those guys are important to you.
And if they're there for something, that's as special as when you're in high school and your mom and dad are at an event.
So you have a different circle of really good, close friends that are important to you.
Was buying that Aggie ring important?
Oh, yeah.
I think that's always been important.
How much did that cost?
And that was all your money?
Yes.
You had earned it.
Yeah.
And I never knew whether the rumor was that the association paid for half of it, but I've been told and never have honestly looked into it.

that no that the rate that ball for sets is what you pay and it I know that it changes from year to year because uh when my daughter bought her Aggie ring in 82 about three or four years later she priced rings and they were cheaper
because gold had gone down and she was told by the ring clerk over there that it depended on the price of gold and there was a time when gold was very high and has been off of course recently.
Do you have any ring stories?
Have you had any interesting experiences?
Well the only thing that happened is when

A&M became coed and non compulsory military I had several of my classmates to send me their rings as class agent and I had four rings for probably five years and then they got in touch with me all of them now gradually got in touch with me and said would I send it back
So I did.
But I had four rings that were sent to me by classmates that said, I'll never wear this again.
But over the years, they reclaimed their rings.
You never lost yours.
Yeah, I lost mine in a crawdad hole out here near the river in Brazos County.
I knew what hole it was in.
Never could find it.
So it's still out there.
I know where it is.
I know where the crawdad hole was.
And I bought a newer.
What about, have you had any good ring stories of where somebody somewhere far away recognized?
We've had several rings that we have tracked down the 59er that have come in to the association office.
Kathy Dockwaller, who was on the staff over the association for years, always was helpful in running down the owners of those rings.
And that was always an interesting experience, took considerable time, and surprisingly some of them didn't want their rings back.
Yeah.

your senior year what were your feelings when you did that final review just I was relieved that it was over with because I I knew what I was going to do at that time I was entering graduate school had a job so final review was
A fun experience, but at the same time was not one that left an indelible mark on me.
I remember it was so hot out there and several people passed out.
I can remember that from being out of tension for a considerable period of time.
Now, who came for commencement and final review?
Generally parents.
We had quite a few parents that would come in for final review.
And did anybody, by then, are you married by then?
No.
Didn't get married until a month later after graduating.
But she, was she here?
Yes.
For?
Yeah.
Janiece came over for final review.
And who, commencement, describe commencement in your day.
Trying to think who spoke, it was in G. Raleigh.
We received our diplomas by marching across the stage, I suspect very similar as today, but everybody graduated with one service.
We didn't have multiple services required.
Every name was called, every hand shaken.
Yes.
Roger Fellman did it, and he did it.
I don't know.
He's probably not doing it today, but here just a few years ago, Roger was still one of those who read off the names and pronounced them as they came across the stage.
And there was no monkey business?
No.
We didn't celebrate on stage.
As you were preparing to go out
into life how did well prepared did you feel A&M had made you for the real world?

I was confident that I could handle that but I had also made the decision that if I was going to ever go anywhere in entomology that I had to get a PhD so I started that even though I had a job I took
made plans initially to take time off to go back and get my masters and ultimately a Ph.D. but that was just a start.
I recognized that in this profession to do what I wanted to do that you had to have a Ph.D. Now it wasn't required at that time for an area extension entomologist but by 65 it was.
Alright as you look back
Were there some life-changing events that occurred
